                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Minister
                            <persName type="to">Lyon</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1909-02-18">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 18, 1909</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mr. Bacon informs Mr. Lyon that it is reported that the Liberian situation is
                    most disquieting, and that there is every need of maintaining order and
                    upholding the constitutional Liberian Government. Mr. Bacon says that any
                    misguided popular opposition now can only precipitate grave questions and make
                    very difficult the effective influence of the United States, and urges the
                    maintenance of initiated reform, stable reorganization of financial
                    administration, faithful observance of international obligations, and security
                    for foreign life and property. Adds that this Government is about to send a
                    commission to Monrovia to report concerning the situation and to counsel
                    prudence.</p>
            </div>
